  <p style="font-size: 1.1em; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 2em;">
    <strong>To join a cannabis club in Madrid, you need three things: a valid passport or national ID, a verified invitation from an existing member, and €20–€50 for the membership fee.</strong> Once you have an invitation, the actual joining process takes 10–15 minutes—you'll show your ID at the door, fill out a short membership form, pay the fee, and walk out with your member card ready to purchase. This guide walks you through every step, from getting your first invitation to understanding what happens when you actually arrive at the club.
  </p>

  <h2 id="overview">How Cannabis Clubs Work</h2>

  <p>Cannabis social clubs in Madrid operate in a legal gray area that's been carefully maintained since the early 2000s. They're not shops. They're not licensed businesses in the traditional sense. They're private clubs—associations formed by members who collectively grow and share cannabis. The law allows private consumption and cooperative cultivation, but sales to the general public remain illegal. Cannabis clubs exist because they're technically not "selling"—they're operating as member cooperatives where everyone contributes to a shared grow and shares the harvest.</p>

  <p>We've walked dozens of tourists through this process over the past five years, and the first thing they misunderstand is what a club actually is. Most expect something like a Dutch coffeeshop—a retail operation where you walk in off the street, order, and leave. That's not what happens. Instead, clubs are membership-based communities. You join as a member. The club has inventory grown collectively or sourced legitimately. Members purchase from that inventory at cost-plus pricing. The whole operation runs on the fiction (maintained in good faith by legitimate clubs) that this is a private, non-commercial activity.</p>

  <p>Most legitimate clubs operate between 11am and midnight, though hours vary. Weekday afternoons (especially Tuesday through Thursday between 2pm–5pm) tend to be quieter. Weekends and evenings are busier, particularly Friday and Saturday nights when locals and tourists flood the clubs. Some clubs close Monday or Tuesday to manage inventory and do accounting. A good club—one that's been operating for a decade or more—has established relationships with law enforcement and city officials. The police aren't arresting people inside legitimate clubs; that line was drawn a long time ago.</p>

  <h2 id="requirements">Requirements to Join</h2>

  <p>The barriers to entry are intentionally minimal, but they exist for important reasons: age verification, identity confirmation, and some level of screening against problematic behavior.</p>

  <h3>Age Requirement</h3>
  <p>You must be at least 21 years old. Some clubs are more lenient and accept 18+, but 21 is the standard. Clubs verify this by checking your ID. If you're under the stated age, you won't get in. Legitimate clubs take this seriously—it's part of their legal defense.</p>

  <h3>Valid Identification</h3>
  <p>You'll need a valid form of ID. For tourists, a passport is ideal. EU nationals can also use a national ID card. Non-EU tourists should carry their passport. No club will accept a driver's license alone, a photocopy, or a photo on your phone. Bring the original document. We've seen tourists turned away at the door because they only had a hotel key card and a driver's license. Don't be that person.</p>

  <h3>An Invitation</h3>
  <p>This is the key requirement, and it's the part that confuses most first-timers. You cannot walk into a cannabis club and join without an invitation from someone already inside the club. Some clubs maintain a "waiting list" or have staff who can verify invitations, but you still need that connection. This is the single biggest hurdle for tourists.</p>

  <p>How do you get an invitation if you don't know anyone in Madrid? Through legitimate guides, hotel concierges who work with clubs, online forums (Reddit's r/Madrid has active cannabis club communities), or connecting with locals through tourist groups. Some hotels near Malasaña and Lavapiés have relationships with clubs and can arrange introductions. Some clubs have partnerships with hostel staff. We tell tourists: if you're staying in a hostel in the city center, ask the staff. They usually know someone.</p>

  <h3>Membership Fee</h3>
  <p>The one-time membership fee ranges from €20 to €50, depending on the club. This pays for your membership card, admin costs, and their insurance/legal protection. Some clubs have higher membership fees (€50–€100) but include a welcome credit for your first purchase. Bring cash—most clubs prefer cash and some don't accept card payments at all. Have €70–€100 minimum in your pocket: €30–€50 for membership, and at least €40–€50 for your first purchase.</p>

  <h3>What You Don't Need</h3>
  <p>Despite myths circulating online, you do not need: a Spanish address, an NIE (Spanish identity number), proof of residency, a recommendation letter, or membership in some "legitimate" guide service. Legitimate clubs accept tourists with just a passport, an invitation, and cash. If a club is demanding anything beyond this, it's a red flag.</p>

  <h2 id="step-by-step">Step-by-Step Process</h2>

  <div class="steps">
    <div class="step">
      <span class="step__number">1</span>
      <div>
        <strong>Secure Your Invitation</strong>
        <p>Before you even head to a club, you need an invitation from someone who's already a member. Ask your hostel staff, hotel concierge, or connect with locals through online communities. The invitation is usually a text message, WhatsApp message, or a name: "Ask for Carlos, tell him Juan sent you." Some clubs have a WhatsApp number you can message to request entry and have staff verify your invitation. Once you have the connection, you're ready for the next step. This typically takes a few hours to a day or two if you're asking around town.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <span class="step__number">2</span>
      <div>
        <strong>Locate the Club and Plan Your Route</strong>
        <p>Cannabis clubs in Madrid are concentrated in four main neighborhoods: Malasaña (the historic heart, with dozens of clubs), Lavapiés (gritty, diverse, many clubs), Chamberí (quieter, more upscale clubs), and Tetuán (residential, fewer clubs but some quality operations). Look up the club's address on a map. Check the train or metro stop closest to it. Plan to arrive during their posted hours—don't show up at 11:45pm expecting to join if they close at midnight. Bring your passport, your invitation details, and cash. Wear something unremarkable; blend in. These neighborhoods get plenty of tourists, but showing up in a neon tourist outfit draws unnecessary attention.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <span class="step__number">3</span>
      <div>
        <strong>Approach the Door and Present Your Invitation</strong>
        <p>Most legitimate clubs have a discreet entrance—a door that doesn't advertise "cannabis club" on a sign. There might be a buzzer or a peephole window. You knock or buzz. A staff member answers. You say something like: "Hi, I'm here to join. I have an invitation from [person's name]" or "I'm a friend of [person's name]." The staff member will either recognize the name, verify it through their system, or ask the member to confirm over the phone. This takes a few minutes. If your invitation is legitimate and the name checks out, you'll be welcomed inside. If not, you'll be turned away politely but firmly.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <span class="step__number">4</span>
      <div>
        <strong>Show Your ID and Fill Out the Membership Form</strong>
        <p>Once inside, a staff member will ask to see your ID. Hand over your passport. They'll copy your name and birthdate—sometimes they'll photograph your passport page. They'll ask a few basic questions: your nationality, where you're from, your age (confirmed). Then you'll sign a membership form. This form is usually one page and states that you're joining as a member of the club, agreeing to their rules (which typically include: don't resell, don't cause trouble, respect other members, follow age/ID requirements). The entire process takes 5–10 minutes. Staff at legitimate clubs speak at least basic English, sometimes fluent English. If they're having trouble understanding you, ask if someone else is available; don't pretend to understand and then cause confusion.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <span class="step__number">5</span>
      <div>
        <strong>Pay the Membership Fee and Receive Your Card</strong>
        <p>Pay your fee in cash. €20–€50 is standard. You'll receive a membership card—sometimes a laminated piece of plastic with a number, sometimes a more formal card. Some clubs also give you a welcome credit (€10–€20) toward your first purchase. Ask about this before you pay; it's not universal, but some clubs build it in. Keep this card. You'll need it each time you visit.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <span class="step__number">6</span>
      <div>
        <strong>Browse the Menu and Make Your First Purchase (Optional)</strong>
        <p>You're now a member, but making a purchase on your first visit is optional. Some people just join, take their card, and leave. Others head straight to the counter. The staff will show you the available strains, prices (usually €6–€12 per gram), and sometimes samples. Cannabis clubs typically offer flowers (dried buds), pre-rolled joints, hashish, and sometimes edibles. Prices are fair compared to the street—you're paying for quality and safety. Staff can recommend based on what you like: uplifting or relaxing, indoor or outdoor grown, THC percentage if labeled. Make your purchase and you're done.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

