  <h2 id="what-to-expect">What to Expect on Your First Visit</h2>

  <p>Walking into a cannabis club for the first time is not like walking into a bar or a shop. The space is often small—sometimes just two rooms. One room is a lounge area with sofas, a TV, maybe some board games. The other is the sales counter. The lighting is usually dim, the music is low or absent, and people are generally quiet and focused. This is not a party scene.</p>

  <p>The atmosphere varies wildly by club. Some are more clubby—colorful, energetic, full of people smoking and socializing. Others are sterile and clinical, almost like a pharmacy. Most fall somewhere in between: chill, respectful, and organized. You'll see regulars sitting on sofas, chatting quietly or working on laptops. You'll see tourists like yourself looking around, asking questions. Occasionally a staff member will be chatting with a regular about new inventory or upcoming events.</p>

  <p>The smell is—cannabis. Pungent, unmistakable, sometimes overwhelming if you're not used to it. Good clubs manage ventilation reasonably well. Expect it anyway. Your clothes will smell like it when you leave. That's part of the experience.</p>

  <p>Staff are professional. They're not your friends, but they're not cold either. They answer questions about strain effects, pricing, and club rules. If you ask about what you should buy as a first-timer, they'll give you honest advice. Many have been doing this for years. They see hundreds of tourists. They know what works for people who are new to cannabis.</p>

  <p>Socially, you can keep to yourself completely. No one will pressure you to socialize. However, if you want to chat with locals or other tourists in the lounge area, that's fine too. Some of the best travel connections happen in cannabis clubs—people are relaxed, time moves slowly, conversations meander. We've seen tourists make friends in clubs and meet up later in the week.</p>

  <p>Consumption rules vary by club. Most allow you to smoke inside. Some have designated smoking areas. A few are strict no-smoking zones (you join, buy, and leave to consume elsewhere). Ask the staff about their policy when you arrive. Most clubs sell rolling papers, lighters, and sometimes bongs and pipes if you need equipment.</p>

  <h2 id="tourists-vs-residents">Tourists vs Residents</h2>

  <div class="comparison-box">
    <div>
      <h4>Tourists</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Invitation requirement:</strong> Must have a verified invitation from a member or through a guide service</li>
        <li><strong>ID requirement:</strong> Passport required; national IDs from EU countries accepted</li>
        <li><strong>Membership fee:</strong> Usually €20–€50, same as residents</li>
        <li><strong>Club access:</strong> Can join any club and be a member of multiple clubs</li>
        <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Temporary membership, typically valid for your stay (a few days to a few weeks)</li>
        <li><strong>Questions asked:</strong> Staff are curious about where you're from, how long you're staying, if this is your first time in Madrid</li>
        <li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Clubs appreciate tourist revenue; you're often treated well because clubs want good reviews and return visits from other tourists</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h4>Residents</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Invitation requirement:</strong> First membership requires an invitation; subsequent club memberships easier once you have one club's card</li>
        <li><strong>ID requirement:</strong> Spanish NIE (foreigner ID number), Spanish driver's license, or passport</li>
        <li><strong>Membership fee:</strong> Same €20–€50, sometimes discounts for annual memberships</li>
        <li><strong>Club access:</strong> Can join multiple clubs; often develop relationships with staff and become regulars</li>
        <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Permanent membership valid year-round, sometimes with annual renewal</li>
        <li><strong>Questions asked:</strong> Where do you live? Do you work nearby? Are you a regular? How did you hear about us?</li>
        <li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Over time, residents build rapport with staff, get insider deals, invited to private events, and become part of the community</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>The practical difference is minimal for most tourists. You'll join, buy, and probably never see that club again. Residents are building long-term relationships. But on a single visit, you have access to the same inventory, same prices, and same experience as a resident would on their first day.</p>

  <h2 id="red-flags">How to Spot a Fake Club</h2>

  <div class="alert--danger">
    <p><strong>Fake clubs exist.</strong> They prey on tourists by taking their membership fee and having no legitimate inventory, or worse, they're set up to rob tourists. Learning to identify fake clubs is the most important skill for a safe cannabis club experience in Madrid.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Major Red Flags</h3>

  <p><strong>They solicit you on the street.</strong> Legitimate clubs don't recruit. If someone approaches you on the street in Malasaña saying "Hey, want to join a club?" or "Need cannabis?" they're either fake or scamming. Legitimate clubs rely on word-of-mouth and existing member invitations. A staff member or known guide might approach you in specific contexts (like a hostel), but it's always in a calm, professional manner—not aggressive street-level recruitment.</p>

  <p><strong>They have a sign, website, or public advertising.</strong> Cannabis clubs operate in legal gray areas. Legitimate clubs are discreet. They don't advertise on storefronts. They don't have flashy websites with "cannabis club" in big letters. They might have a simple website for members, but nothing public-facing. If you Google the name and there's a big website with a shop-like interface, that's likely fake.</p>

  <p><strong>They don't verify your ID properly.</strong> Real clubs photograph your passport, copy your information, and keep records. If they just glance at your ID and wave you in without verification, that's fake. They're not building a legitimate member database.</p>

  <p><strong>No membership card or forms.</strong> Legitimate clubs give you a tangible membership card and have you sign documents. If you pay and walk out with nothing, you're not a member—you just handed over money.</p>

  <p><strong>Prices seem too low or they're pushy about larger purchases.</strong> A gram for €3? That's fake. Real clubs price at €6–€12 per gram depending on quality. If a staff member is aggressively pushing you to buy large amounts or offering "special deals" just for today, it's a scam. Real clubs are patient. They know you're a tourist and you'll be back or you won't, but they don't pressure.</p>

  <p><strong>The location doesn't match the address you were given.</strong> Scammers give fake addresses in nice neighborhoods, then take you to a different sketchy location. Use Google Maps to verify the address before you go. If the directions don't match or staff tell you "the location moved," walk away.</p>

  <p><strong>They ask for more money after you've already paid membership.</strong> Some fake clubs charge a membership fee, then pressure you to pay "entrance fees," "security deposits," or other charges. Membership fee is membership fee. That's it.</p>

  <p><strong>The person inviting you isn't actually a member of that club.</strong> If someone tells you "Oh, I know someone at Club X" but can't verify that person works there or isn't calling to confirm you, don't trust it. Call the club directly with a question (like "What are your hours?") and confirm they exist and are legitimate.</p>

  <p><strong>No English spoken and staff seem confused by basic questions.</strong> Legitimate clubs have English speakers or translation apps. They can explain their rules, prices, and process clearly. If staff seem evasive or confused, leave.</p>

  <h2 id="tips">What We Tell Every First-Timer</h2>

  <p><strong>Bring more cash than you think you need.</strong> If you're planning to spend €40, bring €80. Clubs don't have ATMs in every room. Some don't have ATMs at all. Running out of cash mid-membership is frustrating. An extra €20 buys you peace of mind.</p>

  <p><strong>Go on a weekday afternoon if you're anxious.</strong> The club experience is completely different on a Tuesday at 3pm versus a Saturday at 10pm. Tuesday afternoons are quiet. Staff have time for questions. You can take your time, understand the process, feel less rushed. If you're nervous, that's the best time to go. Weekends are packed, loud, and faster-paced.</p>

  <p><strong>Don't smoke in the club if you're new to cannabis.</strong> Some tourists buy their first cannabis, then try smoking it inside the club lounge. If you're sensitive or it's your first time ever, the last place you want to be uncomfortable is in a public space. Buy it, go back to your hotel or a park, and use it there. You have full control and can manage your experience better.</p>

  <p><strong>Ask staff for recommendations based on your experience level.</strong> Say: "I've never tried cannabis before" or "I prefer relaxing effects." Legitimate staff will point you toward appropriate strains. They won't sell you 18% THC weed to a first-timer and expect you to handle it.</p>

  <p><strong>Understand that your membership card is proof you're a member—protect it.</strong> If you lose it, you can usually get a replacement by returning to the club, but it's a hassle. Keep it in your wallet or a safe place in your hotel room. Some tourists treat it like a souvenir and lose it.</p>

  <p><strong>Don't take photos inside the club.</strong> It's disrespectful to other members, against the rules of most clubs, and unnecessary. The memory is enough. Some clubs have explicit no-photos policies and will kick you out if you try.</p>

  <p><strong>Respect the culture.</strong> These are community spaces. Locals have been coming to the same clubs for years. Don't be loud, don't be demanding, don't try to negotiate prices. You're a guest. Act like one.</p>

  <p><strong>If you want to buy multiple strains or larger amounts, ask about bulk discounts ahead of time.</strong> Some clubs offer slight discounts if you buy an ounce versus a gram. But don't expect retail shops—these are cooperatives. Prices are what they are.</p>

  <p><strong>Know what to expect quality-wise.</strong> Madrid's clubs stock decent-to-excellent quality cannabis. You won't get premium Amsterdam-level genetics in every club, but legitimate clubs maintain good standards. If the flower looks moldy, smells wrong, or the staff seem indifferent to quality questions, that's a sign the club isn't legitimate or isn't taking care of their inventory.</p>

  <p><strong>Remember that your membership is usually temporary if you're a tourist.</strong> Some clubs will let you use your card if you return to Madrid in a month. Others invalidate memberships after a certain period. Ask the staff before you leave: "If I come back in six weeks, can I use this card?" They'll tell you. Don't assume.</p>

  <p><strong>Finally, understand that cannabis use in Spain remains legally ambiguous.</strong> What you're doing (private consumption as a club member) is decriminalized and tolerated, but it's not 100% legally protected. Don't carry cannabis outside the club. Don't smoke in public. Don't take it across borders. Keep your purchase experience contained within the club and your private accommodation. The worst-case scenario for most tourists is being asked to leave a club or a neighborhood, which is rare. The real risk is getting caught with cannabis in public or transporting it, which brings legal consequences.</p>

  <p>By following this process, getting a legitimate invitation, joining a real club, and respecting the space, your experience will be safe, smooth, and memorable. Thousands of tourists do this every month in Madrid without incident. You can too.</p>
